1.1 Download reference transcriptome GTF file

1.1.1 Let’s make a new folder to do today’s exercises in

mkdir ~/rnaseq
cd ~/rnaseq

1.1.2 Download from Ensembl FTP site using wget

  • How to find the URL if you don’t want to type it in:
    • Google: “Ensembl ftp”, should be the first link
    • Direct link: http://useast.ensembl.org/info/data/ftp/index.html/
    • Click on the link for “Mouse” and “Gene sets (GTF)”
    • Right-click on the line “Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf.gz” and copy to clipboard
    • In the terminal: type “wget”, paste in the link. Note, the download will go faster if you change “http” to “ftp”:
## NOTE: ENSEMBL updates these annotations regularly, so the
## link may be slightly different, and the contents slightly different
## from what we report below
wget ftp://ftp.ensembl.org/pub/release-113/gtf/mus_musculus/Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf.gz
  • Downloaded file: Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf.gz

Note: you can find links to the whole genome fasta file and GTF file for mouse from the same Ensembl site, if you were to run the gene-level quantification approach.

1.2.3 Create run_STAR_alignment.sh script

  • Open the run_STAR_alignment.sh script for editing using nano
nano run_STAR_alignment.sh
  • Edit the script to look like this (the STAR command should be in a single line):
#!/bin/sh
#SBATCH --mail-type=BEGIN,END,FAIL
#SBATCH --time=10:00:00
#SBATCH --mem=100G
#SBATCH --ntasks=4
#SBATCH --account=ric_workshop
#SBATCH --partition=batch
#SBATCH -o %x.o%J

cd $SLURM_SUBMIT_DIR
module load STAR

gzip -d Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf.gz

STAR --genomeDir mm39_STAR --runThreadN 8 --sjdbGTFfile Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf 
 --readFilesCommand zcat 
 --readFilesIn control_S4_L001_R1_001.fastq.gz control_S4_L001_R2_001.fastq.gz 
 --outFileNamePrefix Control_S4_STAR
 --outSAMtype BAM Unsorted --quantMode GeneCounts

 gzip Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf
  • Save the script by pressing Ctrl+O then exit nano using Ctrl+X

1.2.4 Then submit the script. We will return to the lecture while the script is running.

  • This will take about 17 minutes to run
sbatch run_STAR_alignment.sh

1.2.6 Infer strandedness from the output using R

ALL REMAINING STEPS FOR THIS EXERCISE ARE ON YOUR COMPUTER!

  • Make a directory called ‘workshop’ on your desktop.
  • Open R Studio and change the working directory to ‘workshop’

  • Now set ‘workshop’ folder as your working directory

  • Download the counts file to your computer with WinSCP (Windows) or CyberDuck (Mac)

Use the SFTP client of your choice to download the Control_S4_STARReadsPerGene.out.tab file to your computer. Make sure it is in the workshop directory.

data <- read.table("Control_S4_STARReadsPerGene.out.tab", row.names=1, sep="\t")

colnames(data) <- c("Unstranded", "Forward", "Reverse")

# Subset to only rows with gene expression counts
data_subset <- data[grepl("^ENSMUSG", rownames(data)), ]

# Calculate the sum of counts for each column
col_sums <- colSums(data_subset[, c("Unstranded", "Forward", "Reverse")])

#Infer strandedness
forward <- col_sums["Forward"]

reverse <- col_sums["Reverse"]

#Unstranded if the difference between forward and reverse is very small. 
#Otherwise, forward or reverse stranded depending on which column sum is greater.
if (abs(forward - reverse) / max(forward, reverse) < 0.1) { 
  strandedness <- "Unstranded"
} else if (forward > reverse) {
  strandedness <- "Stranded (reads match gene strand)"
} else {
  strandedness <- "Stranded (reads are antisense to gene)"
}

cat("Inferred strandedness:", strandedness)
Inferred strandedness: Stranded (reads match gene strand)

1.3 Build Kallisto index

1.3.1 Copy SLURM_template.sh to the current folder

cd ~/rnaseq
cp ~/SLURM_template.sh index.sh

1.3.2 Create index.sh script

  • Open the index.sh script for editing using nano
nano index.sh
  • Edit the script to look like this:
#!/bin/sh
#SBATCH --mail-type=BEGIN,END,FAIL
#SBATCH --time=10:00:00
#SBATCH --mem=100G
#SBATCH --ntasks=4
#SBATCH --account=ric_workshop
#SBATCH --partition=batch
#SBATCH -o %x.o%J

cd $SLURM_SUBMIT_DIR

module load kallisto
kallisto index -i mm39.idx Mus_musculus.GRCm39.cdna.all.fa.gz
  • Save the script by pressing Ctrl+O then exit nano using Ctrl+X

1.3.3 Then submit the script

  • This will take about 5 minutes to run
sbatch index.sh

Note: if the script fails for some reason, you can copy our pre-built index ln -s /workshops/ric_workshop/common/4_RNAseq/mm39.idx

2.2 Gene filtering in R

2.2.1 Filtering on DE stats

# sort genes by significance: we can order on PValue because sometimes there are ties 
# in the QValue. But, ordered by PValue will also be ordered by QValue.
diff.sorted <- diff[order(diff$PValue),]
head(diff.sorted)
# filter genes by significance
degs.diff <- diff[diff$QValue < 0.05,]
dim(degs.diff)
[1] 4134    4
# filter genes by significance AND fold-change
degs.diff2 <- diff[diff$QValue < 0.05 & abs(diff$logFC) > 1,]
dim(degs.diff2)
[1] 2071    4

# Specify the path to your gzipped GTF file
gtf_file <- "Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf.gz"

# Import the GTF file into R (handles gzipped files automatically)
gtf_data <- import(gtf_file, format = "gtf")

# Filter the data to include only gene features
genes <- gtf_data[gtf_data$type == "gene", ]

# Extract gene IDs and gene symbols into a data frame
gene_info <- data.frame(
  gene_id = genes$gene_id,
  gene_symbol = genes$gene_name
)

# Annotate the differential analysis results with the gene symbols (may read from saved file or URL)
# Will be used later for volcano plots

diff <- read.table("diff.txt", row.names=1, header=T, sep="\t")

diff <- read.table("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/RNAseq/diff.txt", row.names=1, header=T, sep="\t")

matching_indices <- match(rownames(diff), gene_info$gene_id)
diff$gene_symbol <- gene_info$gene_symbol[matching_indices]
write.table(diff, "diff_annotated.txt",sep="\t",quote=F,col.names=NA)

2.3 PCA plot

  • Use the normalized expression data.
# Read in the normalized data table from the saved file or our public URL

norm <- read.table("norm.txt",header=T,row.names=1)

norm <- read.table("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/RNAseq/norm.txt",header=T,row.names=1)

# log-scale the data first (this is good practice, as gene expression varies
#    over several orders of magnitude)
# add a pseudo-count (0.1) to avoid taking the log of 0
norm.log <- log2(norm + 0.1)
# run PCA on the transpose of cpm.log: we want to plot the SAMPLES
# Here we don't need to use SCALE=T, because it's normalized expression so the 
#    average expression per SAMPLE should be the same
pca <- prcomp(t(norm.log))

# Create a data frame from PCA results
pca_df <- data.frame(
  PC1 = pca$x[, 1],
  PC2 = pca$x[, 2],
  Name = colnames(norm)
  )

pca_df
#Add sample information from the metadata file

metadata <- read.table("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/RNAseq/metadata.txt",header=T)
metadata
pca_df <- merge(pca_df, metadata, by = "Name")
pca_df
# Plot using ggplot2

#Install and load the ggplot2 and ggrepel packages, if not done previously. 
if(!require(ggplot2)) install.packages("ggplot2")

  #indicate that this is a dotplot
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  #create labels positioned to stay on the plot and not overlap
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = Name), show.legend = FALSE) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Control" = "red", "Disease" = "blue")) +
  labs(x = "PC1", y = "PC2") +
    theme_classic() + #creates plain white background
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# check percent variation per PC
summary(pca)

2.4 Heatmap

library(ComplexHeatmap)
# Get a list of the differentially expressed genes, using a more stringent Q-value
degs.diff <- diff[diff$QValue < 0.01,]
# subset the log-scaled CPMs to get the same genes
degs.cpm <- norm.log[rownames(degs.diff),]
# we do want to z-score across the genes, to account for gene-to-gene
#    differences in baseline expression
# need to transpose twice, as the scale function works on columns
degs.cpm.z <- t(scale(t(degs.cpm)))
# heatmap, without gene names (too many) and label the color key
Heatmap(degs.cpm.z,show_row_names=F,name="Z-scored log2 CPM")

2.5 Volcano plot

  • Use the annotated differential expression data. We will make a basic plot and a plot with coloring, labels, and dashed lines using ggplot2, and then label top 10 genes using ggrepel.
diff <- read.table("diff_annotated.txt", header=T, row.names=1)

# May also read from public URL if file not saved previously 

diff <- read.table("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/RNAseq/diff_annotated.txt", header=T, row.names=1)

# Add a category column for color mapping
diff$category <- "NS"
diff$category[diff$logFC > 0 & diff$QValue < 0.05] <- "Upregulated"
diff$category[diff$logFC < 0 & diff$QValue < 0.05] <- "Downregulated"



#Install the ggplot2 and ggrepel packages, if not done previously
if(!require(ggplot2)) install.packages("ggplot2")
if(!require(ggrepel)) install.packages("ggrepel")

library(ggplot2)
library(ggrepel)

#Transform q values to put the most significant genes on top
diff$logQ = -log10(diff$QValue)

#Make a basic volcano plot
ggplot(diff, aes(x=logFC, y=logQ)) +
  geom_point()

# Add coloring, labels, and dashed lines (you can add to the previous plot commands to save time).
ggplot(diff, aes(x=logFC, y=logQ, color=category)) +
  geom_point() +
  #Vertical lines marking 2-fold up- and downregulation cutoffs
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-1, 1), linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  #Horizontal line marking significance cutoff
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Upregulated" = "red", "Downregulated" = "blue", "NS" = "gray")) +
  #color="" removes the color legend title
  labs(x = "Log2 Fold Change", y = "-log10(Q-value)", title = "Volcano Plot", color = "") +
  theme_classic()

#Label top 10 up- and downregulated genes using geom_text_repel()

# Select top 10 genes by smallest QValue
top_up <- diff[diff$category == "Upregulated", ]
top_up <- top_up[order(top_up$QValue), ][1:10, ]

top_down <- diff[diff$category == "Downregulated", ]
top_down <- top_down[order(top_down$QValue), ][1:10, ]

# Combine top genes for labeling
top_genes <- rbind(top_up, top_down)

ggplot(diff, aes(x=logFC, y=logQ, color=category)) +
  geom_point() +
  #Vertical lines marking 2-fold up- and downregulation cutoffs
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-1, 1), linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  #Horizontal line marking significance cutoff
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Upregulated" = "red", "Downregulated" = "blue", "NS" = "gray")) +
  #color="" removes the color legend title
  labs(x = "Log2 Fold Change", y = "-log10(Q-value)", title = "Volcano Plot", color = "") +
  theme_classic() +
  geom_text_repel(data = top_genes, aes(label = gene_symbol), color = "black")

\Mus_musculus.GRCm39.dna.primary_assembly.fa.gz

  • Create script build_STAR_index.sh

  • Open the build_STAR_index.sh script for editing using nano
nano build_STAR_index.sh
  • Edit the script to look like this (the STAR command should be in a single line):
#!/bin/sh
#SBATCH --mail-type=BEGIN,END,FAIL
#SBATCH --time=24:00:00
#SBATCH --mem=100G
#SBATCH --ntasks=4
#SBATCH --account=ric_workshop
#SBATCH --partition=batch
#SBATCH -o %x.o%J

cd $SLURM_SUBMIT_DIR

module load STAR
STAR --runMode genomeGenerate --genomeDir mm39_STAR 
 --genomeFastaFiles Mus_musculus.GRCm39.dna.primary_assembly.fa 
 --sjdbGTFfile Mus_musculus.GRCm39.113.gtf --sjdbOverhang 100
  • Run SLURM script:
sbatch build_STAR_index.sh

#!/bin/sh
